I read the first part.  Basically it the opinion of those signed that the war is wrong.  I must admit, they threw up a good argument as to what's wrong.<br>
<br>
But then I got to the bottom half and they blew it. Again, this is the classic spin scenario.  Partial truth imbedded with a lot of conjecture.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Traditionally, &quot;defense&quot; means defense of national territory. On September 11, an attack actually took place on and against U.S. territory.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
National territory also includes holdings outside of geographic boundaries.  Embassies, military bases, etc. are also considered national terrority.  U.S. embassies have been attacked and don't forget the U.S.S. Cole.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>This was not a conventional attack by a major power designed to seize territory. Rather, it was an anonymous strike against particular targeted institutions.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
